      So many other things
   =20
 =20

Let=E2=80=99s do=C2=A0an FTX lightning round:
=09Due to=C2=A0some combination of the speed of its collapse and the casual=
ness of its accounting and governance,   FTX did a =E2=80=9Cfreefall=E2=80=
=9D bankruptcy filing, without any prepared first-day motions or declaratio=
ns. (Here is  the filing.)=C2=A0Ordinarily in a bankruptcy you get, pretty =
early on, a declaration from some senior officer kind of explaining what we=
nt down. Here we are still waiting for that.=09Customers are, obviously, un=
happy =E2=80=94=C2=A0including retail customers of FTX US, a separate entit=
y that was supposed to be insulated from FTX international, but that seems =
to have =E2=80=9Cstopped processing withdrawals Friday after the bankruptcy=
 filing.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09FTX was also an=C2=A0institutional exchange, and =
some number of crypto hedge funds seem to have gotten caught with  their mo=
ney trapped at FTX.=09Withdrawals from FTX.com were mostly shut down as it =
imploded, but some off-ramps were open. For instance  Justin Sun=E2=80=99s =
Tron blockchain provided a credit facility allowing people to, effectively,=
 withdraw Tron=E2=80=99s tokens from FTX. This led to FTX customers dumping=
 other assets to buy Tron assets so they could get out. If you are a blockc=
hain entrepreneur, =E2=80=9Cbuy=C2=A0my token because even if your exchange=
 collapses you=E2=80=99ll still be able to get your money back=E2=80=9D is =
kind of a good pitch?=09Another off-ramp is that for a while=C2=A0Bahamas r=
esidents  could take their money out,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cper our Bahamian HQ=E2=
=80=99s regulation and regulators.=E2=80=9D But then the Securities Commiss=
ion of the Bahamas  put out a statement on Saturday saying, no, actually, =
=E2=80=9Cthe Commission wishes to advise that it has not directed, authoriz=
ed or suggested to FTX Digital Markets Ltd. the prioritization of withdrawa=
ls for Bahamian clients,=E2=80=9D and that those withdrawals might be voida=
ble in bankruptcy. Oops?=09That Bahamas off-ramp led to a weird nonfungible=
 token trade, where Bahamas residents could create NFTs, sell them at absur=
d markups on FTX to non-Bahamian customers, take out the proceeds and then =
transfer the proceeds to an outside wallet of the non-Bahamian customer. He=
re is more from  Aleksandar Gilbert at the Defiant. =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98This =
appears to be the first recorded case of NFT utility in existence,=E2=80=99=
=C2=A0crypto influencer Cobie sarcastically tweeted early Friday.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0=09I guess FTX got hacked? =E2=80=9CSam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s bankr=
upt digital-asset exchange FTX was hit by a mysterious outflow of about $66=
2 million in tokens in the past 24 hours,=E2=80=9D   reported Bloomberg New=
s on Saturday.=09=E2=80=9CFTX=E2=80=99s  list of investors spans powerful a=
nd well-known investment firms: NEA, IVP, Iconiq Capital, Third Point Ventu=
res, Tiger Global, Altimeter Capital Management, Lux Capital, Mayfield, Ins=
ight Partners, Sequoia Capital, SoftBank, Lightspeed Venture Partners, Ribb=
it Capital, Temasek Holdings, BlackRock and Thoma Bravo.=E2=80=9D I suppose=
 FTX is a failure of venture capitalist due diligence, but it=E2=80=99s an =
odd kind. The usual VC due diligence failure is, like, you back an entrepre=
neur who promises a futuristic product, and the product doesn=E2=80=99t wor=
k. FTX worked fine: People liked its technology, and it seems to have made =
money. The problem was in its balance sheet, which was full of snakes, and =
its governance, which put all the snakes there. Ideally the venture capital=
ists would have spotted that in due diligence, but the typical VC company h=
as a very simple balance sheet and terrible governance, so it is sort of un=
derstandable that they sailed right by those problems.=09=E2=80=9CFTX=E2=80=
=99s Sam Bankman-Fried was interviewed by Bahamian police and regulators on=
 Saturday,=E2=80=9D   obviously.   And: =E2=80=9CThe Bahamian police said t=
hey=E2=80=99re working with the Bahamas Securities Commission to investigat=
e whether there was any criminal misconduct in the collapse of the crypto e=
xchange FTX.=E2=80=9D  And: =E2=80=9CThe Manhattan U.S. attorney=E2=80=99s =
office is investigating FTX=E2=80=99s collapse.=E2=80=9D=09=E2=80=9CBankman=
-Fried=E2=80=99s Cabal of Roommates in the Bahamas Ran His Crypto Empire =
=E2=80=93 and Dated. Other Employees Have Lots of Questions,=E2=80=9D was a=
=C2=A0brisk and informative  CoinDesk headline last week.=09=E2=80=9CBig In=
vestors Are Giving Up on Crypto Markets Going Mainstream,=E2=80=9D ha.=09Mi=
chael Lewis was somehow there for all of this, and is=C2=A0already  selling=
 the=C2=A0movie rights.=09=E2=80=9CSam Bankman-Fried is not very good at Le=
ague of Legends,=E2=80=9D reports the Financial Times.=C2=A0

Also   this is not FTX news but it is funny: =E2=80=9CCrypto.com said it re=
covered almost $400 million in cryptoasset Ether from Asian exchange Gate.i=
o, after it accidentally transferred the funds to the wrong account.=E2=80=
=9D Not now, Crypto.com!

