=80=99re siphoning off $8 billion to your affiliated trading firm in a hidd=
en account, you might siphon off a round $8 billion, but lots of uncoordina=
ted customer withdrawals are not going to add up to exactly $5 billion even=
. The point here is that FTX appears to have had no real accounting system =
for customer withdrawals? Just sort of take a guess and chuck it in an Exce=
l sheet?


  [2] There is also a truly nightmarish calculation of =E2=80=9Cactual leve=
rage=E2=80=9D (high) and =E2=80=9Cperceived leverage=E2=80=9D (zero) that I=
 do not ever want to think about. =E2=80=9CPerceived leverage=E2=80=9D!


  [3] CoinDesk reported this weekend: =E2=80=9COn Saturday, DeFi protocols =
across the Solana ecosystem began unplugging from Serum for fear that they =
didn=E2=80=99t know who wielded control =E2=80=93 a concern fueled by the l=
ate-Friday hack at FTX. The developers once associated with Serum have gone=
 silent. Meanwhile, the protocol=E2=80=99s dependence on Bankman-Fried and =
his bankrupt companies Alameda and FTX loomed large.=E2=80=9D And The Block=
 reported yesterday: =E2=80=9CSolana founder Anatoly Yakovenko noted that d=
evelopers are rushing to fork Serum=E2=80=99s code today and resume the pro=
tocol without the involvement of FTX. Developers need another version of Se=
rum because the original can only be updated via a private key that was con=
trolled by someone at FTX and not the Serum DAO. As a result of the FTX hac=
k, that key may have been compromised.=E2=80=9D


  [4] Were those reports true? I don=E2=80=99t think you can really tell on=
e way or the other from the Financial Times=E2=80=99s leaked balance sheet,=
 which seems to be for the FTX/Alameda consolidated group, and which does n=
ot exactly follow accounting best practices. But I do think those reports r=
emain plausible; as we will discuss in the next section, the best guess as =
to where FTX=E2=80=99s customer money went was pretty much to Alameda. =E2=
=80=9CFTX=E2=80=99s Digital Coin Was at Heart of Crypto Exchange=E2=80=99s =
Fall,=E2=80=9D the Wall Street Journal reported today, though =E2=80=9Cit c=
ouldn=E2=80=99t be determined if FTT was used as collateral for the custome=
r loans.=E2=80=9D


  [5] Also a little bit of rolled-over stock in Elon Musk=E2=80=99s Twitter=
 Inc. deal?


  [6] So =E2=80=94 if you wanted to do math to these numbers, which I do no=
t recommend =E2=80=94 you could sort of reconstruct a rough =E2=80=9Cbefore=
 last week=E2=80=9D balance sheet that is like $14 billion of customer liab=
ilities, $6 billion of liquid assets, $4 billion of illiquid assets, and $1=
4 billion of FTX-associated tokens, for a total of $24 billion of assets an=
d $10 billion of net equity. (Then you subtract $5 billion from customer li=
abilities and $5 billion from liquid assets to reflect customer outflows la=
st weekend, and you get the =E2=80=9Cbefore this week=E2=80=9D numbers in F=
TX=E2=80=99s spreadsheet.) This reconstructed balance sheet is *less bad* t=
han the one I describe in the text, because it has $6 billion of liquid ass=
ets against $14 billion of customer liabilities, which seems like sort of a=
 plausible amount of liquidity for ordinary circumstances. (Versus the $1 b=
illion of liquidity against $9 billion of liabilities in the actual spreads=
heet.) But it is still very bad deep down, because you=E2=80=99ve got $10 b=
illion of net equity but $14 billion of that is stuff you made up. If you l=
ose confidence, that all goes to zero and you=E2=80=99re insolvent. (I am e=
xaggerating here by counting Solana tokens in the =E2=80=9Cstuff you made u=
p,=E2=80=9D but that was only about $2.2 billion of the $14 billion, so eve=
n if you move it to the =E2=80=9Cliquid=E2=80=9D category the point still h=
olds.)


  [7] FTX could have paid *Alameda* for those tokens =E2=80=94 or taken tho=
se tokens as collateral for loans to Alameda =E2=80=94 but as a consolidate=
d-group matter no money flowed out of the system for those tokens.


  [8] The  Petition newsletter today discusses speculation about this possi=
bility, and reports on the fallout from FTX=E2=80=99s implosion for the *ot=
her* imploded crypto platforms that FTX/Alameda had agreed to bail out.


  [9] See about 31:45 in   this video.


  [10] See also Byrne Hobart=E2=80=99s post today about Bankman-Fried, util=
itarianism, and more-than-full-Kelly betting. You can construct some weird =
utilitarianism that is like =E2=80=9Cit is optimal to constantly gamble cus=
tomer money on crypto bets in order to maximize your chances of stopping a =
malignant AI from destroying humanity.=E2=80=9D=20


