<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is so much, but I want to start with Ser=
um.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a troubled company has a few days to beg po=
tential investors for a bailout before it files for bankruptcy, and it send=
s those investors its balance sheet so they can consider investing, and the=
y all pass, and then the company files for bankruptcy, of course the balanc=
e sheet was=C2=A0<em>bad</em>. That is not a state of affairs that is consi=
stent with a pristine fortress balance sheet.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is a range of possible badness, even=
 in bankruptcy, and the balance sheet that Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s fail=
ed crypto exchange FTX.com sent to potential investors last week before fil=
ing for bankruptcy on Friday is very bad. It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0an Excel file f=
ull of the howling of ghosts and the shrieking of tortured souls. If you lo=
ok too long at that spreadsheet,=C2=A0you will go insane. Antoine Gara, Kad=
him Shubber and Joshua Oliver at the Financial Times=C2=A0<a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQ=
uY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZjA1ZmU5ZjgtY2EwYS00OGQ1LThlZjItN2E0ZDgxM2FmNTU4/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB55a1eae9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">reported on Saturday</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s main international=
 FTX exchange held just $900mn in easily sellable assets against $9bn of li=
abilities the day before it collapsed into bankruptcy, according to investm=
ent materials seen by the Financial Times.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The largest portion of those liquid assets lis=
ted on a FTX international balance sheet dated Thursday was $470mn of Robin=
hood shares owned by a Bankman-Fried vehicle not listed in Friday=E2=80=99s=
 bankruptcy filing, which included 134 corporate entities.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Seems bad, but it somehow keeps getting worse:=
</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A spreadsheet listing FTX internat=
ional=E2=80=99s assets and liabilities, seen by the Financial Times, point =
at the issues that brought Bankman-Fried crashing back down to earth. It re=
ferences $5bn of withdrawals last Sunday, and a negative $8bn entry describ=
ed as =E2=80=9Chidden, poorly internally labled =E2=80=98fiat@=E2=80=99 acc=
ount=E2=80=9D.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What.</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The vast majority of FTX Trading=
=E2=80=99s recorded assets are either illiquid venture capital investments =
or crypto tokens that are not widely traded, according to the spreadsheet, =
which cautions that the figures =E2=80=9Care rough values, and could be sli=
ghtly off; there is also obviously a chance of typos etc. They also change =
a bit over time as trades happen.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What.</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In all, the spreadsheet says FTX T=
rading=E2=80=99s assets were $900mn of =E2=80=9Cliquid=E2=80=9D assets, $5.=
5bn of =E2=80=9Cless liquid=E2=80=9D assets consisting of crypto tokens, an=
d $3.2bn of illiquid private equity investments. There is also an obscure $=
7mn holding called =E2=80=9CTRUMPLOSE=E2=80=9D. There are no bitcoin assets=
 listed, despite bitcoin liabilities of $1.4bn.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What. And yet bad as all of this is, it can=E2=
=80=99t prepare you for the balance sheet itself, <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2N=
vbnRlbnQvMGMyYTU1YjYtZDM0Yy00Njg1LThhOGQtM2M5NjI4ZjFmMTg1/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBdafff2b4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> published by FT Alphaville</a>, which is less a =
balance sheet and more a list of some tickers interspersed with hasty apolo=
gies. If you blithely add up the =E2=80=9Cliquid,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cless li=
quid=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cilliquid=E2=80=9D assets, at their =E2=80=9Cdeli=
verable=E2=80=9D value as of Thursday, and subtract the liabilities, you do=
 get a positive net equity of about $700 million. (Roughly $9.6 billion of =
assets versus $8.9 billion of liabilities.) But then there is the =E2=80=9C=
Hidden, poorly internally labeled =E2=80=98fiat@=E2=80=99 account,=E2=80=9D=
 with a balance of negative $8 billion.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"=
#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t actually think that you=E2=80=99re supposed to su=
btract that number from net equity =E2=80=94 though I do not know how this =
balance sheet is supposed to work! =E2=80=94 but it doesn=E2=80=99t matter.=
 If you try to calculate the equity of a balance sheet with an entry for HI=
DDEN POORLY INTERNALLY LABELED ACCOUNT, Microsoft Clippy will appear before=
 you in the flesh, bloodshot and staggering, with a knife in his little pap=
er-clip hand, saying =E2=80=9Cjust what do you think you=E2=80=99re doing=
=C2=A0Dave?=E2=80=9D You cannot apply ordinary arithmetic to numbers in a c=
ell labeled =E2=80=9CHIDDEN POORLY INTERNALLY LABELED ACCOUNT.=E2=80=9D The=
 result of adding or subtracting those numbers with ordinary numbers is not=
 a number; it is prison.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But here is the paragraph that drove <em>me=C2=
=A0</em>insane:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company=E2=80=99s biggest asse=
t as of Thursday was $2.2bn worth of a cryptocurrency called Serum. Serum=
=E2=80=99s market value was $88mn on Saturday, according to data provider C=
ryptoCompare, suggesting FTX=E2=80=99s holdings would be worth far less if =
sold into the market. CryptoCompare=E2=80=99s figures take into account the=
 coin=E2=80=99s liquidity.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you look on the balance sheet, that=E2=80=
=99s the biggest =E2=80=9Cdeliverable=E2=80=9D number: $2,187,876,172 of SR=
M, the ticker for the Serum token, down from $5,430,110,335 =E2=80=9Cbefore=
 this week.=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=9CBefore this week=E2=80=9D means, of course, =
before=C2=A0<em>last=C2=A0</em>week =E2=80=94=C2=A0before the week that FTX=
 was circulating this spreadsheet =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I will use it as a sho=
rthand to mean roughly =E2=80=9Cbefore Nov. 8.=E2=80=9D On Nov. 8, the trou=
ble at FTX became public, and everything FTX-related crashed.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As of about 11 a.m. today, <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb2lubWFya=
2V0Y2FwLmNvbS9jdXJyZW5jaWVzL3NlcnVtLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB159eb044" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> CoinMarketCap showed</a> the Serum token having a price of $0.25,=C2=
=A0a =E2=80=9Cmarket cap=E2=80=9D of about $65 million and a =E2=80=9Cfully=
 diluted market cap=E2=80=9D of about $2.5 billion. Those numbers would hav=
e been a bit higher =E2=80=94=C2=A0say $0.35 to $0.40 per token =E2=80=94 o=
n Thursday, when this balance sheet was created. The price crashed last Tue=
sday, during FTX=E2=80=99s death throes; before that the token=C2=A0traded =
around $0.80. In round numbers FTX probably held something like two-thirds =
of Serum=E2=80=99s fully diluted market cap, and roughly 20 <em>times</em> =
its basic market cap.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In crypto, market cap is (as CoinMarketCap put=
s it) =E2=80=9Cthe total market value of a cryptocurrency's circulating sup=
ply =E2=80=A6=C2=A0analogous to the free-float capitalization in the stock =
market,=E2=80=9D while fully diluted market cap is =E2=80=9Cthe market cap =
if the max supply was in circulation.=E2=80=9D So if for instance some comp=
any creates a token, and says that there can be 10 billion of the token, an=
d reserves them all for=C2=A0itself, and then sells 1 million of them to ou=
tside investors for $1 each, then the market cap=C2=A0of that token is $1 m=
illion ($1 times 1 million circulating tokens), while the fully diluted mar=
ket cap is $10 billion ($1 times 10 billion total tokens), and the issuer=
=E2=80=99s 9,999,000,000 remaining tokens have a value, on this math, of $9=
.999 billion. We will come back to this point.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is Serum? <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJvamVjdHNlcnVtL=
mNvbS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa3ec45d9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Serum is</a>=C2=A0a =E2=
=80=9Cprotocol for decentralized exchanges that brings unprecedented speed =
and low transaction costs to decentralized finance=E2=80=9D that runs on th=
e Solana blockchain. Also Serum (the token, ticker SRM)=C2=A0=E2=80=9C<a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM=
6Ly9kb2NzLnByb2plY3RzZXJ1bS5jb20vaW50cm9kdWN0aW9uL3NybS10b2tlbg/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBdc39ac9b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">is the utility and governance token</a> of =
Serum (the protocol). If you hold SRM in your wallet, you receive a discoun=
t on fees=E2=80=9D for trading on the Serum protocol. Also, when the protoc=
ol collects trading fees, it uses a portion of the fees to buy and burn SRM=
. The result is that SRM functions a lot like stock in Serum: If the Serum =
project does well and a lot of decentralized trading happens on its exchang=
es, then it will collect a lot of fees and use those fees to buy SRM, which=
 will drive up the value of SRM and make SRM investors rich. (Also the SRM =
investors can vote on how Serum is run.) If you are bullish on Serum as a b=
usiness, as a platform for decentralized crypto trading, then you should bu=
y SRM, because SRM is more or less a claim on the cash flows of that busine=
ss.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that is really really really really =
really important to mention about the Serum=C2=A0protocol is that it was <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0=
cHM6Ly9tZWRpdW0uY29tL3NvbGFuYS1sYWJzL2Z0eC1jaG9vc2VzLXNvbGFuYS1mb3Itc2VydW0=
tYS1oaWdoLXNwZWVkLW5vbi1jdXN0b2RpYWwtZGVjZW50cmFsaXplZC1kZXJpdmF0aXZlcy1leG=
NoYW5nZS1jMzQ2YTI3YzFmMmI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbf7daec2" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> creat=
ed</a>=C2=A0and=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY29pbmRlc2suY29tL21hcmtldHMvMjAyMS8wNC8y=
OC9zZXJ1bS10b2tlbi1iZWNvbWVzLWxhdGVzdC1wcm9qZWN0LWluLWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQtZW1=
waXJlLXRvLXR1cm4taGVhZHMv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB119d15d3" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">promot=
ed</a> by FTX and Alameda Research, the FTX-affiliated crypto hedge fund th=
at was also founded by Bankman-Fried. FTX is a centralized crypto exchange,=
 but a lot of people in crypto do not trust centralized exchanges (for reas=
ons!) and prefer to trade on decentralized exchanges. Serum is, in a loose =
but meaningful way, the decentralized exchange <em>of</em> FTX.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Go back to what I said above, about a company =
creating a token, issuing a bunch of it to itself, and selling a little of =
it into the public market. Something like 3% of the total value of Serum is=
 held by the public and trading on exchanges. The other 97% is not. Somethi=
ng like two-thirds of that 97% is held by FTX and Alameda.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How did they get their SRM? Well, you can look=
 at <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.27751=
9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJvamVjdHNlcnVtLmNvbS9zZXJ1bS10b2tlbi1zdW1tYXJ5/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB470e97c0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the distribution of SRM here</a>, but t=
he main point=C2=A0is that they did=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>buy it on the op=
en market for cash. When FTX=E2=80=99s balance sheet says that, =E2=80=9Cbe=
fore this week,=E2=80=9D it held $5.4 billion worth of Serum, that does=C2=
=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>mean that Alameda or FTX took $5.4 billion of cash (th=
eir own, their investors=E2=80=99, their customers=E2=80=99, anyone=E2=80=
=99s) and used it to buy a lot of Serum tokens in the open market. They got=
 all those Serum tokens for, in round numbers,=C2=A0<em>free</em>, as the i=
nitial backers of the Serum protocol. (Presumably they paid some startup co=
sts.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a minute, ignore this nightmare balance sh=
eet, and think about what FTX=E2=80=99s balance sheet <em>should=C2=A0</em>=
be. Conceptually, customers give you money =E2=80=94=C2=A0apparently about =
$16 billion in dollars, crypto, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then you hang on to=
 the money and owe it back to them. In the simplest world, you keep the cus=
tomers=E2=80=99 money in exactly the form they give it to you: Someone depo=
sits $100, you keep $100 for him; someone deposits one Bitcoin, you keep on=
e Bitcoin for her. For <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS1kZWF0aC1zcGlyYWwtYmVmb=
3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTE0MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVt=
YWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1=
vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB17dcb338" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  reasons we have d=
iscussed</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0some legitimate! =E2=80=94=C2=A0FTX doesn=E2=80=
=99t quite work that way, and you could imagine some more complicated balan=
ce sheet where a lot of the money and crypto that came in from some custome=
rs was loaned to others. But broadly speaking your balance sheet is still g=
oing to look roughly like:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Liabilities:=C2=A0</em>Money customers gav=
e you, which you owe to them;</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Assets: </em>Stuff you bought with that mo=
ney.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the basic question is, how bad is the=
 mismatch. Like, $16 billion of dollar liabilities and $16 billion of liqui=
d dollar-denominated assets? Sure, great.=C2=A0$16 billion of dollar liabil=
ities and $16 billion worth of Bitcoin assets? Not ideal, incredibly risky,=
 but in some broad sense understandable. $16 billion of dollar liabilities =
and assets consisting entirely of some magic beans that you bought in the m=
arket for $16 billion? Very bad. $16 billion of dollar liabilities and asse=
ts consisting mostly of some magic beans=C2=A0<em>that you invented yoursel=
f and acquired for zero dollars? </em>WHAT? Never mind the <em>valuation</e=
m>=C2=A0of the beans; where did the=C2=A0<em>money=C2=A0</em>go? What happe=
ned to the $16 billion? Spending $5 billion of customer money on Serum woul=
d have been horrible, but FTX didn=E2=80=99t do that, and couldn=E2=80=99t =
have, because there wasn=E2=80=99t $5 billion of Serum available to buy. FT=
X shot its customer money into some still-unexplained reaches of the astral=
 plane and was like =E2=80=9Cwell we do have $5 billion of this Serum token=
 we made up, that=E2=80=99s something?=E2=80=9D No it isn=E2=80=99t!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One simple point=C2=A0here is that FTX=E2=80=
=99s Serum holdings =E2=80=94=C2=A0$2.2 billion last week, $5.4 billion bef=
ore that =E2=80=94 could not have been sold for=C2=A0<em>anything like </em=
>$2.2 billion. FTX=E2=80=99s Serum holdings were <em>vastly=C2=A0</em>large=
r than the entire circulating supply of Serum. If FTX had attempted to sell=
 them into the market over the course of a week or month or year, it would =
have swamped the market=C2=A0and crashed the price. Perhaps it could have g=
otten a few hundred million dollars for them. But I think a realistic valua=
tion of that huge stash of Serum would be closer to zero. That is not a com=
ment on Serum; it=E2=80=99s a comment on the size of the stash.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>want to comment on=
 Serum, because=C2=A0Serum is not some weird token that FTX cornered for so=
me reason; Serum is a token that FTX <em>made up</em>. To use a loose but r=
easonable analogy, Serum (the protocol) is sort of FTX=E2=80=99s decentrali=
zed exchange subsidiary, and SRM (the token) is sort of the stock in that s=
ubsidiary. A little of the stock trades publicly, but it is mostly held by =
FTX, its corporate parent, as it were. The public market price of the small=
 free float might give a reasonable estimate of the value of the subsidiary=
. But in the real world, the value of the subsidiary is=C2=A0<em>incredibly=
 tightly linked=C2=A0</em>to the value of FTX=E2=80=99s overall business. I=
f everyone is like =E2=80=9Cah yes FTX is a good exchange operator and a le=
ader in safe crypto trading,=E2=80=9D then its decentralized exchange proto=
col has a good chance of being popular and profitable. If everyone is like =
=E2=80=9Cah yes FTX is a careless fraud,=E2=80=9D then Serum is going to ha=
ve a hard time.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
