<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">But where did it go?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I tried, in the previous section, to capture t=
he horrors of FTX=E2=80=99s balance sheet as it spiraled into bankruptcy. B=
ut, as I said, there is something important missing in that account. What=
=E2=80=99s missing is the money. What=E2=80=99s missing is that FTX had at =
some point something like $16 billion of customer money, but most of its as=
sets turned out to be tokens that it made up. It did not pay $16 billion fo=
r those tokens, or even $1 billion, probably.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Money came in, but then when customers came to FTX and pried open=
 the doors of the safe, all they found were cobwebs and Serum. Where did th=
e money go?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, but the leading story ap=
pears to be that FTX gave the money to Alameda, and Alameda lost it. I am n=
ot sure about the order of operations here. The most sensible explanation i=
s that Alameda lost the money<em> first</em> =E2=80=94=C2=A0during the cryp=
to-market meltdown of this spring and summer, when markets were crazy and A=
lameda=C2=A0spent=C2=A0money propping up=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>failing c=
rypto firms =E2=80=94=C2=A0and <em>then </em>FTX transferred customer money=
 to prop up Alameda. And Alameda never made the money back, and eventually =
everyone noticed that it was gone.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Reuters <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmV1dGVycy5jb20vbWFya=
2V0cy9jdXJyZW5jaWVzL2V4Y2x1c2l2ZS1sZWFzdC0xLWJpbGxpb24tY2xpZW50LWZ1bmRzLW1p=
c3NpbmctZmFpbGVkLWNyeXB0by1maXJtLWZ0eC1zb3VyY2VzLTIwMjItMTEtMTIv/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB5c422d68" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> reported last week</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At least $1 billion of customer funds have van=
ished from collapsed crypto exchange FTX, according to two people familiar =
with the matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The exchange's founder Sam Bankman-Fried secre=
tly transferred $10 billion of customer funds from FTX to Bankman-Fried's t=
rading company Alameda Research, the people told Reuters.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A large portion of that total has since disapp=
eared, they said.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the Wall Street Journal <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3Nq=
LmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9hbGFtZWRhLWZ0eC1leGVjdXRpdmVzLWFyZS1zYWlkLXRvLWhhdmUta25=
vd24tZnR4LXdhcy11c2luZy1jdXN0b21lci1mdW5kcy0xMTY2ODI2NDIzOA/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBd5f7eb36" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> reported over the weekend</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda Research=E2=80=99s chief executive and=
 senior FTX officials knew that FTX had lent its customers=E2=80=99 money t=
o Alameda to help it meet its liabilities, according to people familiar wit=
h the matter. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda faced a barrage of demands from lender=
s after crypto hedge fund Three Arrows Capital collapsed in June, creating =
losses for crypto brokers such as Voyager Digital Ltd., the people said.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a video meeting with Alameda employees late=
 Wednesday Hong Kong time, Alameda CEO Caroline Ellison said that she, Mr. =
Bankman-Fried and two other FTX executives, Nishad Singh and Gary Wang, wer=
e aware of the decision to send customer funds to Alameda, according to peo=
ple familiar with the video. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ms. Ellison said on the call that FTX used cus=
tomer money to help Alameda meet its liabilities, the people said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda had taken out loans to fund illiquid v=
enture investments, the people said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here we are in the realm of pure speculation, =
but you could imagine a number of ways this could have gone:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto prices, and firms, crashed earl=
ier this year, and Alameda spotted a huge opportunity. It deployed as much =
capital as it could into buying great assets at bargain-basement prices. Bu=
t since there was a crypto winter, it couldn=E2=80=99t deploy all that much=
 capital, and was getting calls from its own lenders. So Ellison and Bankma=
n-Fried conferred and sensibly decided that they couldn=E2=80=99t miss this=
 opportunity, and that they would deploy FTX customers=E2=80=99 money again=
st it. They=E2=80=99d make a fortune in short order on can=E2=80=99t-lose t=
rades, and pay back the customer funds with interest. Then, oops, they were=
 wrong. This story is bad =E2=80=94=C2=A0none of these stories are going to=
 be good! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but understandable. If you run an opaque business =
in a lightly regulated industry, and customers trust you with their money, =
and you use it to make what you think are good bets, and those bets turn ou=
t wrong, well, that happens sometimes.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">Crypto prices crashed earlier this year, and Alameda was caught out. I=
t lost money and was facing calls from its lenders. Ellison and Bankman-Fri=
ed realized that Alameda would=C2=A0go under without help, so they took FTX=
 customer money to prop up Alameda, and gambled on redemption. This story i=
s not=C2=A0<em>so=C2=A0</em>different from the previous one, though it is w=
orse, but=C2=A0also very understandable. It is=C2=A0the typical way these t=
hings go, the default assumption for why someone would use customer money. =
No one wants to fail, no one wants to admit that they lost money, and if th=
ere=E2=80=99s a poorly guarded pot of money they can use to paper over loss=
es, sometimes they will.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto pr=
ices, and firms, crashed earlier this year, and FTX/Alameda were like =E2=
=80=9Cwe are in a confidence business, and if we let these firms crash then=
 investors will lose confidence in crypto exchanges, which is bad for our b=
usiness.=E2=80=9D Either in a good, public-spirited, we-want-crypto-to-thri=
ve way, or in a bad, we-need-suckers way, or a bit of both.=C2=A0So they ba=
iled those firms out with customer money. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMTkvYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1zYXlzLWNyeXB0by=
13aW50ZXItc2hpZnRzLWludmVzdG9yLWZvY3VzLXRvLXByb2ZpdD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTE0MjJfT=
U9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVy=
bT0yMjExMTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB488885=
77" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">a video of Bankman-Fried and me</a> discussing this possibilit=
y at the Bloomberg Crypto Summit in July, in which he said:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CT=
he explicit working principle we had=E2=80=9D in these bailouts was that =
=E2=80=9Cwe are incinerating a relatively small-ish amount of money in doin=
g this,=E2=80=9D in order to keep the crypto ecosystem healthy. Alameda/FTX=
 was willing to lose money bailing out other firms, if doing so improved co=
nfidence in crypto generally. Of course we did not talk about the possibili=
ty that FTX was doing this with customer money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Crypto prices, and firms, crashed earlier this year, and FTX/=
Alameda spotted an <em>opportunity to acquire new customer deposits cheaply=
 and use them for nefarious purposes</em>. Like, you pay zero dollars for t=
he equity of some busted crypto lending platform, you roll the customers ov=
er to become FTX customers, you cash out anyone who wants to cash out, you =
assume that most people will trust FTX (their savior) and=C2=A0<em>not=C2=
=A0</em>cash out, and then you use=C2=A0<em>their=C2=A0</em>deposits to fun=
d your wild speculations. If FTX/Alameda were <em>already=C2=A0</em>using c=
ustomer deposits for bad reasons, and losing them, then acquiring more cust=
omer deposits would be a way to keep things going.<a class=3D"footnote-inde=
x" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displa=
y: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">FTX/Alameda were funnel=
ing customer money into lavish lifestyles for their executives. This one do=
es not seem likely here =E2=80=94=C2=A0they <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTEvc2FtLWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQtZm9vbGVkLXRoZS1j=
cnlwdG8td29ybGQtYW5kLW1heWJlLWV2ZW4taGltc2VsZj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTE0MjJfTU9ORVl=
TVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMj=
ExMTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB76c466fe" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">  slept on beanbag chairs in the office</a>, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but =
it is <em>in general</em> a very common explanation of missing customer mon=
ey, and you=E2=80=99d want some accounting.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">FTX/Alameda were funneling customer money into effective altruism=
. Bankman-Fried seems to have generously funded a lot of effective altruism=
 charities, artificial-intelligence and pandemic research, Democratic polit=
ical candidates, etc. One $500 million entry on the desperation balance she=
et is =E2=80=9CAnthropic,=E2=80=9D a venture investment in an <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29694056.277519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZGI0MTVhZTktOTM4ZC00NWJkLWE4YjctNTEwY2UyZWRjOTQz/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB9ff13cf6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">AI safety company</a>. At that same B=
loomberg Crypto Summit, I asked Bankman-Fried<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>: =E2=80=9CYou are sort of in the business of funneling money from peop=
le who are going to use it poorly on gambling to, like, animal charities an=
d pandemic preparedness and Joe Biden. Is that too cynical a view, or is th=
at not cynical at all, or what?=E2=80=9D My question assumed that FTX and A=
lameda made a lot of money on fees and spreads from running a crypto exchan=
ge and=C2=A0market-maker, so they were <em>legitimately</em> taking=C2=A0mo=
ney from gamblers and using it for charity. But =E2=80=9Cnot cynical enough=
=E2=80=9D might have been the correct answer.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ul>
